{Qualitative Evaluation}
Model B demonstrated a far superior understanding of conversational coherence within the context of the character. Its responses created a logical and compelling arc that mirrored the character's journey in the film. It began with full-throated bravado, then, when pressed, revealed the painful justification for its "shield," and finally, described the bleak reality of what happens when that shield breaks. Each answer built logically on the last, escalating the intensity and vulnerability in a way that felt authentic.

Model A, in contrast, failed to establish a coherent persona. It immediately jumped to the end of the character's emotional journey, presenting a self-aware, apologetic individual from the very first response. While its answers were loosely consistent with each other (a narrative of someone already in recovery), they were completely incoherent with the starting persona of Frank T.J. Mackey. This created a major contradiction from the outset and failed to capture the dramatic tension of the character's facade crumbling over time. Model B's responses felt like a real, evolving conversation; Model A's felt like a summary of a character's arc., [Scores]: (3, 9)
